==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|avis|lang=fro}}, from the {{etyl|fro|en}} phrase ''ce m'est a vis'' ("in my view"), where {{term|vis|lang=fro}} is from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|visum|lang=la}}, past participle of {{term|videre||to see|lang=la}}. See {{term|vision}}, and confer {{term|avise}}, {{term|advise}}. The unhistoric -d- was introduced in English 15c.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-advice.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ədˈvaɪs/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ædˈvaɪs/}}
* {{rhymes|aɪs}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# An [[opinion]] [[recommend]]ed or [[offer]]ed, as [[worthy]] to be [[follow]]ed; [[counsel]].
#: ''We may give '''advice''', but we can not give conduct.'' &mdash; Franklin.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Deliberate [[consideration]]; [[knowledge]].
#: ''How shall I dote on her with more '''advice,''' That thus without '''advice''' begin to love her?'' &mdash; Shakespeare.
# Information or notice given; intelligence; as, late advices from France; commonly in the plural. In commercial language, advice usually means information communicated by letter; used chiefly in reference to drafts or bills of exchange; as, a letter of advice.
#: {{rfquotek|McElrath}}
# {{context|legal|lang=en}} Counseling to perform a specific [[illegal]] act.
#: {{rfquotek|Wharton}}
# {{context|computing|programming|lang=en}} In [[aspect-oriented]] programming, the code whose [[execution]] is triggered when a [[join point]] is reached.

